snippet.title: KIDS WORKOUT(NO EQUIPMENT)
snippet.description:
If your kids have been driving you crazy this lockdown try this simple bodyweight routine to get them active and healthy. 

Workouts for kids comes with tons of benefits including ;
* Better concentration
* stronger heart, bones and healthier muscles
* Improved self-esteem
* Encourages healthy growth and development and much more.

Routine🏃‍♂️
Starjumps 30sec + Stair run x 3
Stair Climb x 10
Burpee Lateral jump x 10reps
Push-ups x 10reps
Spiderman Crawl x 30sec
Step-Ups x 10reps per side
Clean & Press x10reps

If you enjoyed the video please like, share and subscribe
Cheers🤙

snippet.title: HealthWorks! Youth Fitness 301 - Cardio with Weights | Cincinnati Children's
snippet.description:
http://www.cincinnatichildrens.org

Learn how to burn calories doing cardio with weights

This exercise video series is part of the HealthWorks!, a family-based program at Cincinnati Children's Heart Institute to help overweight kids and teens learn healthy habits.

HealthWorks! is one of the first of its kind and is the cornerstone of the pioneering Center for Better Health and Nutrition, a national role model in combating childhood obesity that treats more than 500 patients annually.

HealthWorks! uses a variety of methods to help overweight children and teens – and their families – improve eating habits and become more physically active. The program is designed to work with the lifestyle and needs of the young person and the immediate family, helping them to set realistic, achievable goals.

In addition to promoting more physical activity, we emphasize making changes to the daily diet that include and promote healthier eating habits.

Learn more at:
https://www.cincinnatichildrens.org/service/b/better-health/healthworks

* Disclaimer: Please be advised that there are known risks involved in participating in any exercise program. All exercise and other forms of physical activity can be dangerous, especially if performed without medical advice and proper supervision. Always consult your physician or health care professional before beginning any exercise program. Cincinnati Children’s.

snippet.title: Exercises to treat your Children's Intoeing | The Best Exercise Circuit
snippet.description:
Welcome back folks to another Feet&Co video! Folks, especially parents, guardians and kids, intoeing is common in my practice and it really lead me to write up, plan, shoot and edit THIS VIDEO because as a parent myself, when you see your child or anyone in your social circle walk with their feet intoeing, you get a little bit concerned. 

In this video, I will show you a simple workout that anyone from 1 year old to 1000 years old can do to help correct their intoeing and restore better equilibrium to their walking, running and jumping!    Let’s gooo!

Alrighty folks, thank you for watching my video and if you have any questions and comments, then please drop them in the comments below the video! And also, if you’re finding the content relatable, enjoyable and insightful, then let’s stay in touch by you punching that ‘subscribe button’ and tapping that ‘bell button’ to stay in the ‘know’ when new content arrives!


Do you know why your child or you walk with intoeing? Or pigeon toes? 3 main reasons : metatarsus adductus, nternal tibial torsion   , increased femoral anteversion.

Folks, this is not a WHY AND HOW VIDEO. There’s plenty of it on Google and YouTube, however, I’ll link an article I wrote a while ago that will go through Intoeing. 

This video is about taking ACTION dammit! We need to take action to make change. 
1/ The first action I request you do is to watch and enjoy this video! Take notes if you need too! 

2/ The second action is to make an appointment with your local Podiatrist who specialises in children so that they can assess the extent of intoeing. The truth is, if the extent of intoeing is quite severe on imaging and physical assessments, surgery is a possibility. However, I understand that you may not want that or be comfortable with that. Go see your local Podiatrist. 

3/ The third action is to APPLY this simply exercise circuit for 15-20 minutes a day. If you’re an adult, add this to your exercise workout, if you’re a busy parent, then you have my permission to act like a kid and make this a fun and interactive workout with your children! Ok? It’s spending quality time with your children.

Remember the goal of this workout is strengthen hip and thigh muscles to encourage more hip outward rotation and reduce hip inward rotation! Thereby reducing intoeing! 

[SEND ME YOUR VIDEOS DOING THIS WORKOUT ON INSTAGRAM - TAG ME @THE_FOOT_MECHANIC WITH THE HASHTAG #FEETANDCO so i can have a look!]

Ok, so here is the program which I call the “The Penguin” workout. 

THE PENGUIN WORKOUT

1/  Big Bear walks
2/ Sumo Frog Jumps
3/ Cheeky Crab Walks
4/ Penguin Walks

I want you and your kids to do each workout 5-10 reps [define reps] as a progressional circuit. They will repeat this circuit at least 3-4 times. 

I’m going to demonstrate this workout! Firstly, prepare the training area - outdoor, grass, soft surface areas with markers to map out the course. The great thing is that your course can be straight or with turns whichever fits well with your home or outdoor area! Once set up, Then you can proceed. 


What did you think folks?! Hmm. i thought it was a pretty good video! Now folks, I’d love for you to share you and your family’s playtime doing The Penguin workout on my Instagram by tagging my Insta name  : @the_foot_mechanic and hashtag it with #feetandco!

Ok! That’s it for me on this video, but if you have any questions and or comments, post them below and I’ll get to replying asap! 

Oh and don’t forget to check out my recent video about the terrible night cramps! You’ll need to watch it to help your flexibility for the Penguin Workout! 


Cheers

WALK & RUN SMARTER NOT HARDER

snippet.title: Top 8 Reasons to Get Help for your Child: Exercises for a Child with Cerebral Palsy #015
snippet.description:
Meet Sebastian. He is a young boy with Spastic Quadriplegic Cerebral Palsy. His family wants to help me share treatment suggestions to help children like him across the world.  My clinic, Child and Family Development,  in Charlotte, NC, allowed me to use their facilities and their equipment to showcase Sebastian's skill and charming personality. We review techniques to reduce stiffness, encourage strength and control. I think you'll love spending time with him. Thank you to this family and my clinic for allowing this to happen.
 I also have available 3 children's educational books, "A is for Autism," "D is for Down Syndrome," "C is for Cerebral Palsy,"   and now 2 professional books "Pediatric Physical Therapy Exercises for the Hips", and "Pediatric Physical Therapy Exercises for the Knees" available on Amazon.  I have forthcoming "A is for ADHD" as well.  If you have questions or suggestions, feel free to contact me at amysturkey@gmail.com. Please note: I am unable to provide treatment suggestions for a child I have not personally evaluated.

snippet.title: #23 Sitting Propping on a Bench in Front: Exercises for a Child with Cerebral Palsy
snippet.description:
Meet Sebastian. He is a young boy with Spastic Quadriplegic Cerebral Palsy. His family wants to help me share treatment suggestions to help children like him across the world.  My clinic, Child and Family Development,  in Charlotte, NC, allowed me to use their facilities and their equipment to showcase Sebastian's skill and charming personality. We review techniques to reduce stiffness, encourage strength and control. I think you'll love spending time with him. Thank you to this family and my clinic for allowing this to happen.
 I also have available 3 children's educational books, "A is for Autism," "D is for Down Syndrome," "C is for Cerebral Palsy,"   and now 2 professional books "Pediatric Physical Therapy Exercises for the Hips", and "Pediatric Physical Therapy Exercises for the Knees" available on Amazon.  I have forthcoming "A is for ADHD" as well.  If you have questions or suggestions, feel free to contact me at amysturkey@gmail.com. Please note: I am unable to provide treatment suggestions for a child I have not personally evaluated.
I am so honored to have people from all over the world watch my videos. I have reviewed and corrected the closed captions for this video so that you might understand what I am saying even if you don't speak English. I hope the directions below are helpful to you. 
To turn on Captions, click CC in the bottom right corner of the video
To choose a different caption language:
At the bottom right, click Settings. It looks like a wheel.
Click Subtitles/CC.
Select a language.
If the language isn't listed when you click Subtitles/CC:
Click Auto-translate.
Select a language.
